    19→// Since Rust no longer uses jemalloc by default, ripgrep will, by default,
    20→// use the system allocator. On Linux, this would normally be glibc's
    21→// allocator, which is pretty good. In particular, ripgrep does not have a
    22→// particularly allocation heavy workload, so there really isn't much
    23→// difference (for ripgrep's purposes) between glibc's allocator and jemalloc.
    24→//
    25→// However, when ripgrep is built with musl, this means ripgrep will use musl's
    26→// allocator, which appears to be substantially worse. (musl's goal is not to
    27→// have the fastest version of everything. Its goal is to be small and amenable
    28→// to static compilation.) Even though ripgrep isn't particularly allocation
    29→// heavy, musl's allocator appears to slow down ripgrep quite a bit. Therefore,
    30→// when building with musl, we use jemalloc.
    31→//
    32→// We don't unconditionally use jemalloc because it can be nice to use the
    33→// system's default allocator by default. Moreover, jemalloc seems to increase
    34→// compilation times by a bit.
    35→//
    36→// Moreover, we only do this on 64-bit systems since jemalloc doesn't support
    37→// i686.
    38→#[cfg(all(target_env = "musl", target_pointer_width = "64"))]
    39→#[global_allocator]
    40→static ALLOC: tikv_jemallocator::Jemalloc = tikv_jemallocator::Jemalloc;
